.PP
Enter the \fIgen_fsm\fR receive loop.

.PP
Makes an existing process into a \fIgen_fsm\fR process.  Does not return, instead the calling process enters the \fIgen_fsm\fR receive loop and becomes a \fIgen_fsm\fR process.  The process must have been started using one of the start functions in \fIproc_lib\fR.  The user is responsible for any initialization of the process, including registering a name for it.

.PP
This function is useful when a more complex initialization procedure is needed than the \fIgen_fsm\fR behavior provides.

.PP
\fIModule\fR, \fIOptions\fR, and \fIFsmName\fR have the same meanings as when calling \fIstart[_link]/3,4\fR. However, the process must have been registered according to \fIFsmName\fR before this function is called.

.PP
\fIStateName\fR, \fIStateData\fR, and \fITimeout\fR have the same meanings as in the return value of \fIModule:init/1\fR. The callback module \fIModule\fR does not need to export an \fIinit/1\fR function.

.PP
The function fails if the calling process was not started by a \fIproc_lib\fR start function, or if it is not registered according to \fIFsmName\fR.


