\fB              when\fR
\fB                  FsmRef :: fsm_ref(),\fR
\fB                  Reason :: term(),\fR
\fB                  Timeout :: timeout().\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: gen_fsm:stop/3 is deprecated; use the 'gen_statem' module instead
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Synchronously stop a generic FSM.

.PP
Orders a generic finite state machine to exit with the specified \fIReason\fR and waits for it to terminate.  The \fIgen_fsm\fR process calls \fIModule:terminate/3\fR before exiting.

.PP
The function returns \fIok\fR if the generic finite state machine terminates with the expected reason.  Any other reason than \fInormal\fR, \fIshutdown\fR, or \fI{shutdown, Term}\fR causes an error report to be issued using \fIerror_logger:format/2\fR.

.PP
\fITimeout\fR is an integer greater than zero that specifies how many milliseconds to wait for the generic FSM to terminate, or the atom \fIinfinity\fR to wait indefinitely. If the generic finite state machine has not terminated within the specified time, a \fItimeout\fR exception is raised.

.PP
If the process does not exist, a \fInoproc\fR exception is raised.


.RE
.B
\fBsync_send_all_state_event(FsmRef, Event, Timeout) -> Reply\fR
\fB                                   when\fR
\fB                                       FsmRef :: fsm_ref(),\fR
\fB                                       Event :: term(),\fR
\fB                                       Timeout :: timeout(),\fR
\fB                                       Reply :: term().\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: gen_fsm:sync_send_all_state_event/3 is deprecated; use the 'gen_statem' module instead
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Send an event synchronously to a generic FSM.

.PP
Sends an event to the \fIFsmRef\fR of the \fIgen_fsm\fR process and waits until a reply arrives or a time-out occurs.  The \fIgen_fsm\fR process calls \fIModule:handle_sync_event/4\fR to handle the event.

.PP
For a description of \fIFsmRef\fR and \fIEvent\fR, see \fIsend_event/2\fR. For a description of \fITimeout\fR and \fIReply\fR, see \fIsync_send_event/3\fR.

.PP
For a discussion about the difference between \fIsync_send_event\fR and \fIsync_send_all_state_event\fR, see \fIsend_all_state_event/2\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBsync_send_event(FsmRef, Event, Timeout) -> Reply\fR
\fB                         when\fR
\fB                             FsmRef :: fsm_ref(),\fR
\fB                             Event :: term(),\fR
\fB                             Timeout :: timeout(),\fR
\fB                             Reply :: term().\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: gen_fsm:sync_send_event/3 is deprecated; use the 'gen_statem' module instead
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Send an event synchronously to a generic FSM.

.PP
Sends an event to the \fIFsmRef\fR of the \fIgen_fsm\fR process and waits until a reply arrives or a time-out occurs. The \fIgen_fsm\fR process calls \fIModule:StateName/3\fR to handle the event, where \fI'StateName'\fR is the name of the current state of the \fIgen_fsm\fR process.

.PP
For a description of \fIFsmRef\fR and \fIEvent\fR, see \fIsend_event/2\fR.

.PP
\fITimeout\fR is an integer greater than zero that specifies how many milliseconds to wait for a reply, or the atom \fIinfinity\fR to wait indefinitely.  If no reply is received within the specified time, the function call fails.

.PP
Return value \fIReply\fR is defined in the return value of \fIModule:StateName/3\fR

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe ancient behavior of sometimes consuming the server exit message if the server died during the call while linked to the client was removed in Erlang 5.6/OTP R12B.



.RE
.SH CALLBACKS
.LP
.B
\fB'StateName'(Event, StateData)\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: the callback gen_fsm:'StateName'(_,_) is deprecated; use the 'gen_statem' module instead
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Handle an asynchronous event.

.PP
There is to be one instance of this function for each possible \fIstate name\fR. Whenever a \fIgen_fsm\fR process receives an event sent using \fIsend_event/2\fR, the instance of this function with the same name as the current \fIstate name\fR \fIStateName\fR is called to handle the event. It is also called if a time-out occurs.

.PP
\fIEvent\fR is either the atom \fItimeout\fR, if a time-out has occurred, or the \fIEvent\fR argument provided to \fIsend_event/2\fR.

.PP
\fIStateData\fR is the \fIstate data\fR of the \fIgen_fsm\fR process.

.PP
If the function returns \fI{next_state, NextStateName, NewStateData}\fR, \fI{next_state, NextStateName, NewStateData, Timeout}\fR, or \fI{next_state, NextStateName, NewStateData, hibernate}\fR, the \fIgen_fsm\fR process continues executing with the current \fIstate name\fR set to \fINextStateName\fR and with the possibly updated \fIstate data\fR \fINewStateData\fR.  For a description of \fITimeout\fR and \fIhibernate\fR, see \fIModule:init/1\fR.

.PP
If the function returns \fI{stop ,Reason, NewStateData}\fR, the \fIgen_fsm\fR process calls \fIModule:terminate(Reason, StateName, NewStateData)\fR and terminates.


.RE
.B
\fB'StateName'(Event, From, StateData)\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: the callback gen_fsm:'StateName'(_,_,_) is deprecated; use the 'gen_statem' module instead
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Handle a synchronous event.

.PP
There is to be one instance of this function for each possible \fIstate name\fR. Whenever a \fIgen_fsm\fR process receives an event sent using \fIsync_send_event/2,3\fR, the instance of this function with the same name as the current \fIstate name\fR \fIStateName\fR is called to handle the event.

.PP
\fIEvent\fR is the \fIEvent\fR argument provided to \fIsync_send_event/2,3\fR.

.PP
\fIFrom\fR is a tuple \fI{Pid, Tag}\fR where \fIPid\fR is the \fIpid/0\fR of the process that called \fIsync_send_event/2,3\fR, \fITag\fR is a unique tag.

.PP
\fIStateData\fR is the \fIstate data\fR of the \fIgen_fsm\fR process.


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If \fI{reply, Reply, NextStateName, NewStateData}\fR, \fI{reply, Reply, NextStateName, NewStateData, Timeout}\fR, or \fI{reply, Reply, NextStateName, NewStateData, hibernate}\fR is returned, \fIReply\fR is given back to \fIFrom\fR as the return value of \fIsync_send_event/2,3\fR. The \fIgen_fsm\fR process then continues executing with the current \fIstate name\fR set to \fINextStateName\fR and with the possibly updated \fIstate data\fR \fINewStateData\fR. For a description of \fITimeout\fR and \fIhibernate\fR, see \fIModule:init/1\fR.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If \fI{next_state, NextStateName, NewStateData}\fR, \fI{next_state, NextStateName, NewStateData, Timeout}\fR, or \fI{next_state, NextStateName, NewStateData, hibernate}\fR is returned, the \fIgen_fsm\fR process continues executing in \fINextStateName\fR with \fINewStateData\fR.  Any reply to \fIFrom\fR must be specified explicitly using \fIreply/2\fR.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If the function returns \fI{stop, Reason, Reply, NewStateData}\fR, \fIReply\fR is given back to \fIFrom\fR.  If the function returns {stop, Reason, NewStateData}, any reply to \fIFrom\fR must be specified explicitly using \fIreply/2\fR.  The \fIgen_fsm\fR process then calls \fIModule:terminate(Reason, StateName, NewStateData)\fR and terminates.

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBcode_change(OldVsn, StateName, StateData, Extra)\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: the callback gen_fsm:code_change(_,_,_,_) is deprecated; use the 'gen_statem' module instead
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Update the internal \fIstate data\fR during upgrade/downgrade.

.PP
This function is called by a \fIgen_fsm\fR process when it is to update its internal \fIstate data\fR during a release upgrade/downgrade, that is, when instruction \fI{update, Module, Change, ...}\fR, where \fIChange = {advanced, Extra}\fR, is given in the appup file; see Release Handling Instructions in OTP Design Principles.

.PP
For an upgrade, \fIOldVsn\fR is \fIVsn\fR, and for a downgrade, \fIOldVsn\fR is \fI{down, Vsn}\fR. \fIVsn\fR is defined by the vsn attribute(s) of the old version of the callback module \fIModule\fR.  If no such attribute is defined, the version is the checksum of the Beam file.

.PP
\fIStateName\fR is the current \fIstate name\fR and \fIStateData\fR the internal \fIstate data\fR of the \fIgen_fsm\fR process.

.PP
\fIExtra\fR is passed "as is" from the \fI{advanced, Extra}\fR part of the update instruction.

.PP
The function is to return the new current \fIstate name\fR and updated internal data.


.RE
.B
\fBformat_status/2\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: the callback gen_fsm:format_status(_,_) is deprecated; use the 'gen_statem' module instead
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Optional function for providing a term describing the current \fIgen_fsm\fR process status.

.PP
The second argument is \fI[PDict, StateData]\fR, that is, a list with the 2 elements, in that order.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThis callback is optional, so callback modules need not export it. The \fIgen_fsm\fR module provides a default implementation of this function that returns the callback module \fIstate data\fR.


.PP
This function is called by a \fIgen_fsm\fR process in the following situations:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
One of \fIsys:get_status/1,2\fR is invoked to get the \fIgen_fsm\fR status. \fIOpt\fR is set to the atom \fInormal\fR for this case.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
The \fIgen_fsm\fR process terminates abnormally and logs an error. \fIOpt\fR is set to the atom terminate for this case.

.RE

.PP
This function is useful for changing the form and appearance of the \fIgen_fsm\fR status for these cases.  A callback module wishing to change the \fIsys:get_status/1,2\fR return value as well as how its status appears in termination error logs, exports an instance of \fIformat_status/2\fR that returns a term describing the current status of the \fIgen_fsm\fR process.

.PP
\fIPDict\fR is the current value of the process dictionary of the \fIgen_fsm\fR process.

.PP
\fIStateData\fR is the internal \fIstate data\fR of the \fIgen_fsm\fR process.

.PP
The function is to return \fIStatus\fR, a term that change the details of the current state and status of the \fIgen_fsm\fR process. There are no restrictions of the form \fIStatus\fR can take, but for the \fIsys:get_status/1,2\fR case (when \fIOpt\fR is \fInormal\fR), the recommended form for the \fIStatus\fR value is \fI[{data, [{"StateData", Term}]}]\fR, where \fITerm\fR provides relevant details of the \fIgen_fsm\fR \fIstate data\fR. Following this recommendation is not required, but it makes the callback module status consistent with the rest of the \fIsys:get_status/1,2\fR return value.

.PP
One use for this function is to return compact alternative \fIstate data\fR representations to avoid that large state terms are printed in log files.


.RE
